        <body>       

                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>From<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline"></hi>329 E. 51<hi rend="sup">st</hi> St<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. &#91;S.&#93; Morais<lb/>
                546 N. 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/>
                Pa.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Nov. 16<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>Would you kindly let me<lb/> know the address of the man <del>from</del><lb/> whom you wish to induce to send<lb/> his wife a &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I have unfortunately<lb/> mislaid it or I should have attended to<lb/> the matter.  I would also like to<lb/> know what you think of having a<lb/> public exhibition of the Seminary&#44;<lb/> not an examination&#44; exactly&#44; but<lb/> an exhibition&#44; consisting of recitations<lb/> and addresses of the students&#44; officers<lb/> and friends of the Seminary which<lb/> will draw a large assemblage&#44; keep<lb/> us before the public and gain members<lb/> and patrons or donors.  Dr. Mendes and<lb/> I have been speaking the matter over<lb/> and have thought that the steady<lb/> work going on in the classes while in<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>itself very valuable was of too quiet<lb/> a character to keep public attention<lb/> upon us and maintain a lively interest.<lb/>  We thought that such a public<lb/> display&#44; besides enabling us to get<lb/> many members and donors on the<lb/> spot would also draw public attention<lb/> to us and would also give the<lb/> pupils a new incentive to active<lb/> effort.  If this should be decided<lb/> upon at once I would undertake to prepare<lb/> the students so as to be able to<lb/> give the exhibition about the middle of January.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping that you will soon let us<lb/> know your views and sentiments in the<lb/> matter&#44; I remain&#44; with best regards to<lb/> yourself and family<lb/> very sincerely<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
